{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491612"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"998"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/998"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.75,0.12,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"998"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49918"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/998"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-11-07T22:20:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T16:59:28+09:30","updatedAction":"revised","acceptedAt":"2023-03-16T15:47:04+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-27 20:38:42"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"998"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35175"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3475"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13151"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35175"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49918"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the gastroenterology clinic for follow up of her cirrhosis. She was diagnosed two months ago after developing ascites, and was at that time advised sodium restriction, alcohol abstinence, and started on spironolactone and furosemide. The doses of these two drugs were gradually increased to 400 mg/day and 160 mg/day respectively. She has a 15-year history of significant alcohol consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Her abdomen is pictured (Image). She has lost 1.4 kg compared to her last visit two weeks ago. Blood tests show elevated liver enzymes and abnormal clotting function, but normal renal function and electrolytes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence hydrochlorothiazide","Commence carvedilol","Large volume paracentesis","Transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt","Liver transplant workup"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with refractory ascites not responding to maximal diuretic therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003ELarge-volume paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E (LVP) with albumin replacement is a safe and effective first-line treatment for refractory ascites. Paracentesis is the procedure used to remove fluid from the peritoneal cavity, and albumin infusion prevents post-paracentesis circulatory dysfunction. LVP is also sometimes performed for symptomatic relief in patients before reaching maximal diuretic dosing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing hydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best option in this case. It is unlikely to be effective when the patient is already on maximum doses of spironolactone and furosemide, which are the preferred diuretics in liver disease, and carries the risk of worsening electrolyte imbalances and renal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing carvedilol\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-selective beta-blocker, is not the most appropriate next step for managing refractory ascites. Non-selective blockers are often used in patients with cirrhosis to prevent variceal bleeding and are also indicated to prevent decompensation in patients with clinically significant portal hypertension. However, they are generally discontinued in patients with refractory ascites due to their potential to reduce cardiac output and renal perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS)\u003C/strong\u003E decompresses the hypertensive portal vein and hepatic sinusoids without the need for major surgery. It is an option for refractory ascites and may be pursued if the patient requires frequent LVP, but is associated with risks including hepatic encephalopathy. Therefore, the first line for refractory ascites is LVP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver transplant workup\u003C/strong\u003E is likely warranted for this patient with severe liver disease and now refractory ascites and is an important component of her overall management. However, it is not the most immediate next step in management. The priority is to address her acute symptoms and provide relief from the ascites. She will additionally require a longer period of abstinence before she will be considered for liver transplantation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, large-volume paracentesis with albumin replacement is the most appropriate next step for this patient with refractory ascites. It provides immediate symptomatic relief and is the recommended first-line treatment in this scenario. Following this, the patient\u0027s overall management plan, including consideration for TIPS or liver transplantation, can be assessed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Large-volume paracentesis (LVP) with albumin replacement is a safe and effective first-line treatment for refractory ascites and can also be used for symptomatic relief."],"references":["European Association for the Study of the Liver. EASL clinical practice guidelines for the management of patients with decompensated cirrhosis. J Hepatol 2018; 69:406\u2013460."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35175"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"998"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19489"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19489"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/28bc0e8b-74bc-4b8f-bac6-c76eec3f9048.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/28bc0e8b-74bc-4b8f-bac6-c76eec3f9048.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":374,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35175"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-04T16:59:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T16:59:28+09:30","number":13,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"998"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49918"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms"